===Vehicles===
{{main|KITT}}
The car used as [[KITT]] in the series was a customized 1982 [[Pontiac Firebird (third generation)|Pontiac Firebird Trans Am]] sports model, that cost US$100,000 to build&lt;ref&gt;Browning, Norma Lee. &quot;Riding High with Knight Rider&quot;, ''[[Toys R Us]]'' magazine; Vol. 1, No. 2; 1986; p. 5&lt;/ref&gt; (equivalent to about $266,000 in 2018).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=https://data.bls.gov/cgi-bin/cpicalc.pl?cost1=100%2C000.00&amp;year1=198201&amp;year2=201804|title=CPI Inflation Calculator |last= |first= |date= |website=Bureau of Labor Statistics, U.S. Government |publisher=United States Government |accessdate=24 May 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; Nose, dash and other interior of the car were designed by the design consultant Michael Scheffe.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.carlustblog.com/2014/09/the-knight-industries-two-thousand-kitt-behind-the-scanner.html The Knight Industries Two Thousand â€“ K.I.T.T.- Behind the Scanner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620163807/http://www.carlustblog.com/2014/09/the-knight-industries-two-thousand-kitt-behind-the-scanner.html |date=June 20, 2015 }} carlustblog.com&lt;/ref&gt;

The car that was also used as Knight Automated Roving Robot (K.A.R.R.) in the original Knight Rider series.  It was also a customized mechanically and cosmetically modified third generation 1982 Pontiac Firebird Trans Am like K.I.T.T.  K.A.R.R. was the evil vehicular clone of K.I.T.T in Season 1 and his evil return and last appearance in Season 3.

===Soundtrack===
The &quot;Knight Rider Theme&quot; was composed by [[Stu Phillips (composer)|Stu Phillips]] and Glen A. Larson.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0092317 &quot;Knight Rider Theme&quot; sheet music] at musicnotes.com&lt;/ref&gt; The series DVD bonus material contains an interview about this lead music, where Glen A. Larson says he remembers a theme out of a classical piece (&quot;Marche Et CortÃ¨ge De Bacchus&quot; Act III - No. 14 from [[Sylvia (ballet)|Sylvia]] written by French composer [[LÃ©o Delibes]]) from which he took pieces for the &quot;Knight Rider Theme&quot;.

The rest of the series music was composed by Stu Phillips for 13 episodes and Don Peake for 75 episodes. Glen A. Larson co-wrote music for one episode and [[Morton Stevens]] wrote the music for one episode.  Peake took over scoring duties at S1E14 in 1983, when Larson moved to [[Twentieth Century-Fox]] and Phillips was working there on his projects.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;Revving It Up&quot;, liner notes, ''Knight Rider: The Stu Phillips Scores'', FSM Vol. 8, No. 10.&lt;/ref&gt; Peake remained as the series sole composer until the end of the series in 1986, with the exception of &quot;K.I.T.T. vs. K.A.R.R.&quot; in third season, which he composed together with Stu Phillips and Glen A. Larson.

In 2005, FSM released a disc of music from the series, featuring the series theme, ad bumpers and Phillips' scores for &quot;Knight of the Phoenix&quot; (the pilot), &quot;Not a Drop to Drink&quot;, &quot;Trust Doesn't Rust&quot;, &quot;Forget Me Not&quot; and the composer's final episode &quot;Inside Out&quot;, as well as the logo music for Glen Larson Productions. Albums of Don Peake's scores have also been issued.

==Episodes==
{{Main|List of Knight Rider (1982 TV series) episodes}}
{{:List of Knight Rider (1982 TV series) episodes}}

The intro throughout most of the episodes began with this narration:
{{bquote|Knight Rider, a shadowy flight into the dangerous world of a man who does not exist. &lt;br /&gt;
Michael Knight, a young loner on a crusade to champion the cause of the innocent, the helpless, the powerless in a world of criminals who operate above the law.}}

During the first season, the outro was Michael and KITT driving though a road in the desert with Wilton Knight's words of &quot;One man can make a difference, Michael.&quot;

Then the narration goes on to say:&lt;br /&gt;
{{bquote|Michael Knight, a lone crusader in a dangerous world. The world of the Knight Rider.}}

The outro of Seasons 2 and 3 was Michael and KITT driving away from the sunset toward the camera. Season 4's outro was the same, except with KITT in Super Pursuit Mode.

==Syndication and home media==
===In syndication===
''Knight Rider'' was first syndicated in the U.S. in the Fall of 1986.  Stations were initially offered either the original hour-long format (with three minutes cut from each episode), or severely-condensed into half-hour format.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/86-OCR/BC-1986-04-28-OCR-Page-0004.pdf#search=%22knight rider%22&lt;/ref&gt; Reruns were later syndicated on [[USA Network]] in 1994,&lt;ref&gt;Daily Variety Magazine; November 3, 1994 issue; p. 23.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Syfy|Sci-Fi Channel]] in 2003,&lt;ref&gt;http://www.knightrideronline.com/news/2003/01/scifi-launches-knight-rider-we.html&lt;/ref&gt; [[Cloo|Sleuth]] in 2005,&lt;ref&gt;http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/news-articles/nbc-u-uncover-sleuth/71238&lt;/ref&gt; and on [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] in 2012.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://knightrideronline.com/news/2012/10/g4_to_re-air_knight_rider_starting_october_1st.php|title=G4 to re-air Knight Rider starting October 1st - news|publisher=knight rider online}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===DVD releases===
[[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|Universal Studios]] has released all four seasons of ''Knight Rider'' on DVD in regions 1, 2 &amp; 4. A complete series box set featuring all 90 episodes in a collector's edition box has been released in regions 1&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Knight Rider: The Complete Series |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001D2WU8Y |title=Knight Rider: The Complete Series: David Hasselhoff, Edward Mulhare: Movies &amp; TV |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=September 5, 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt; &amp; 2.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000J10L9U |title=Knight Rider&amp;nbsp;â€” The Complete Box Set [DVD&amp;#93;: Amazon.co.uk: David Hasselhoff, Edward Mulhare, Patricia Mcpherson, Julian Alverez, James Young: Film &amp; TV |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=September 5, 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On March 8, 2016, it was announced that [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] had acquired the rights to the series in Region 1; they subsequently re-released the first two seasons on DVD on May 3, 2016.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://tvshowsondvd.com/news/Knight-Rider-Seasons-1-and-2/22067|title=Knight Rider DVD news: Re-Release for Season 1 and Season 2 - TVShowsOnDVD.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311094557/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Knight-Rider-Seasons-1-and-2/22067|archivedate=March 11, 2016|df=mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;  On October 4, 2016, Mill Creek re-released ''Knight Rider- The Complete Series on DVD in Region 1.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://tvshowsondvd.com/news/Knight-Rider-The-Complete-Series/22436|title=Knight Rider DVD news: Announcement for The Complete Series on Blu-ray|publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703002930/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Knight-Rider-The-Complete-Series/22436|archivedate=July 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;

